    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-05-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-05-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="15"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d15">
                <head>15. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (Brzezinski) to President Carter<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d15fn1"
                        >Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material,
                        Subject File, Box 42, Missiles: 2–6/77. Secret. Carter initialed the top of
                        the memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-05-02">May 2, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Sea-Launched Cruise Missiles</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Navy has prepared a briefing on the Tomahawk—our sea-launched cruise missile.
                        <persName corresp="#p_BH_1">Harold Brown</persName> forwarded a copy of the
                    briefing to me noting that the flight profiles and the test program indicate
                    many important facts about the nature and verifiability of cruise missiles that
                    have not received enough attention to date. As you know, the Tomahawk is
                    designed to fit a standard submarine torpedo tube, but it is also capable of
                    being launched from a variety of platforms (see Tab A).<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d15fn2">Attached but not printed.</note> A few highlights from the
                    briefing follow: <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>At Tab B<note n="3" xml:id="d15fn3">Attached but not printed.</note>
                            is a graph depicting comparative cruise missile development for the
                                <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> and the Soviet Union. Cruise
                            missiles, by the way, go back to the German V–1 “buzz bomb”.</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>The Navy’s approach to ensure Tomahawk’s ability to penetrate enemy
                            defenses was to make it fly as low as possible and to reduce its
                            visibility to enemy radars, visual and infra-red detection devices. Here
                            are a few results from the Navy’s test program: <list>
                                <label>•</label>
                                <item>The Tomahawk has flown in actual flight at less than [<hi
                                        rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] above
                                    the terrain.</item>
                                <label>•</label>
                                <item>Ground observations on the flight path were unable to see the
                                    missile until about 10 seconds before overflight. In addition,
                                    neither the ground nor air observers at the target could detect
                                    exhaust smoke from the missile.</item>
                                <label>•</label>
                                <item>The ability of the Tomahawk’s anti-ship missile to attack an
                                    over-the-horizon target has been successfully demonstrated (Tab
                                        C).<note n="4" xml:id="d15fn4">Attached but not
                                        printed.</note>
                                </item>
                                <label>•</label>
                                <item>An <gloss target="#t_SSN_1">SSN</gloss> in the Mediterranean
                                    simulated Tomahawk’s attacks against Soviet ships (Tab D).<note
                                        n="5" xml:id="d15fn5">Attached but not printed.</note> The
                                    tests were successful.</item>
                                <label>•</label>
                                <item>The Tomahawk land-attack missile has demonstrated a range
                                    capability in excess of [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not
                                        declassified</hi>].</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <pb facs="0076" n="51" xml:id="pg_51"/>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>According to the Navy, the principle threats to the Tomahawk missile
                            in the early 1980s will be advanced low-altitude <gloss
                                target="#t_SAM_1">SAM</gloss>s and look-down, shoot-down
                            interceptors. Results of the Navy’s survivability study based on these
                            threats are found at Tab E.<note n="6" xml:id="d15fn6">Attached but not
                                printed.</note>
                            <persName corresp="#p_BH_1">Harold Brown</persName> suggests we should
                            reserve judgment on the vulnerability question since it depends in
                            detail on defenses.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
